Iterators:
     An iterator is an object that lets you access elements one at a time instead of loading everything at once.
     It follows two methods internally:
            __iter__()
            __next__()
     Simple Analogy

        Imagine reading a huge book page by page.

        You do NOT copy the entire book into memory
        You only read the current page
        Then move to the next page

    That is exactly how iterators work.

    How Iterator Works Internally:
            numbers = [10, 20, 30]

            it = iter(numbers)

            print(next(it))   # 10
            print(next(it))   # 20
            print(next(it))   # 30

    What happens internally
            it = numbers.__iter__()
            it.__next__()
    Important Point

        A normal list stores all values in memory.

        An iterator gives values on demand.

        This is called:

            Lazy Evaluation

        Meaning:

            "Produce value only when needed."
    Why Iterators Are Important in Real World

    Without iterators:

        Huge memory usage
        Slow processing
        Cannot handle infinite streams

    With iterators:

        Memory efficient
        Faster streaming
        Handles large datasets
        Works well with files, APIs, Kafka streams, logs
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Generators:

    A generator is a special way to create iterators easily.

    Instead of:
        creating class
        implementing __iter__
        implementing __next__
    Generators gives a simpler way of syntax using yield keyword

    What yield Does

    yield:
        pauses function
        saves state
        resumes later

    When To Use Iterator vs Generator
        Use Iterator When
                You need:
                    complex state management
                    custom object behavior
                    reusable iteration class
                Examples:
                    database cursor
                    Kafka consumer
                    custom framework internals
        Use Generator When

                You need:
                    streaming data
                    memory optimization
                    pipelines
                    simple lazy processing
                    Examples:
                        API streaming
                        reading files
                        ETL jobs
                        ML batches

    Very Important Interview Point
            Every Generator Is an Iterator But Not Every Iterator Is a Generator
            Because:generator automatically implements iterator protocol
Lazy loading
    Lazy loading in Python means deferring the creation or loading of an object/resource until it is actually needed. Instead of doing work upfront, you delay it to improve performance
    reduce memory usage.

        🧠 Core Idea

        “Don’t compute or load something until you really need it.”

        🔧 Why It Matters (Tech Lead Perspective)

        Lazy loading is useful when:

            Initialization is expensive (DB calls, large files, APIs)
            Data may never be used
            You want faster startup time
            You’re optimizing memory footprint

        ⚙️ Common Patterns in Python
                1. Lazy Evaluation with Generators

                Generators compute values on demand.

                def lazy_numbers():
                    for i in range(1000000):
                        yield i

                Values are generated one at a time

                No large list in memory

        2. Lazy Attributes (using @property)

        Load something only when accessed:

        class User:
            def __init__(self):
                self._profile = None

            @property
            def profile(self):
                if self._profile is None:
                    print("Loading profile...")
                    self._profile = self._load_profile()
                return self._profile

            def _load_profile(self):
                return {"name": "Alice"}

        👉 First access → loads data
        👉 Subsequent access → cached result

        3. Lazy Imports

            Delay importing heavy modules:

            def process_data():
                import pandas as pd
                return pd.DataFrame()

            Improves startup time

            Useful in CLI tools / microservices

        4. Using functools.lru_cache

            Cache results of expensive computations:

            from functools import lru_cache

            @lru_cache(maxsize=None)
            def compute(x):
                print("Computing...")
                return x * x

            👉 First call → computes
            👉 Next calls → reused (lazy + memoization)

        5. Proxy Pattern (Advanced)

        Wrap an object and delay its creation:

        class Database:
            def connect(self):
                print("Connecting...")

        class LazyDB:
            def __init__(self):
                self._db = None

            def connect(self):
                if self._db is None:
                    self._db = Database()
                return self._db.connect()
        📊 When to Use vs Avoid
                ✅ Use Lazy Loading When:

                        Expensive operations (I/O, DB, large ML models)

                        Rarely accessed data

                        Improving API responsiveness

        ❌ Avoid When:

                Data is always needed anyway (adds complexity)

                Debugging complexity matters

                Real-time systems needing predictable latency

        ⚠️ Trade-offs
            Benefit	Cost
            Faster startup	First access slower
            Lower memory usage	More complex code
            Avoid unnecessary work	Harder debugging
        🎯 Tech Lead Summary

        Lazy loading is a performance optimization pattern

        Combine with:

            caching (lru_cache)

            async I/O

        Be mindful of:

            hidden latency spikes (first access)

            thread safety if used in concurrent systems
