"If __name__=="__main__":
    Every python file has a special variable called __name__.
    When the file run directly python sets __name==__main__

    When file is imported from another file python sets __name__=="modular name"

    So this condition:
        if __name__=="__main__":
            means:
                Run the code inside the block only when the file is executed directly not when it is imported

        Why is this powerful?
            keeps testing/demo code separate from reusable functions
            prevents unwanted execution when the modules are imported
