15.   In .pyc files, are bytecodes same as while compiling C program?

        1.No - Python.pyc bytecode is not the same as Compiled C program code. they are very different in how they are generated and executed.
        2.When python file execute then .py file is converted to .pyc compiled file (bytecode)
        3.This Bytecode is not machine code it is instruction for Python Virtual Machine(PVM).

     The interpreter reads and executes these instructions one by one
     In c compile produce machine code directly for the cpu (No Virtual machine is needed)

     The Python Virtual Machine (PVM) is the engine inside Python that executes your code. It takes compiled Python bytecode and runs it line by line, acting as the interpreter between your program and the computer’s hardware.
⚙️ Key Points About PVM
        Role: Executes Python bytecode generated from .py files.

        Interpreter: Provides a consistent environment across platforms (Windows, Linux, macOS).

        Stack-based architecture: Uses a stack to evaluate expressions and manage function calls.

        Part of CPython: The default Python implementation includes the PVM.

        Execution model:

            Source code → .py file

            Compilation → Bytecode (.pyc)

            Execution → PVM runs bytecode line by line

🔑 Short Explanation in Simple Lines:

        Python code is first compiled into bytecode.

        The PVM reads and executes this bytecode.

        It works as a software layer between code and hardware.

        Ensures Python runs the same way on different systems.

        Errors during execution are handled by the PVM.

📖 Real-world Analogy

        Think of the PVM as a chef in a kitchen:

        The recipe (Python code) is written in English.

        It’s translated into step-by-step instructions (bytecode).

        The chef (PVM) follows those instructions exactly to prepare the dish.

📊 Quick Comparison Table
        Step	             What Happens	                                       Example
        Source Code	         You write Python (print("Hello"))	                   .py file
        Compilation	         Python converts to bytecode	                       .pyc file
        Execution	         PVM runs bytecode	                                   Output: Hello

✅ In short: PVM is the heart of Python execution. It makes your code run by interpreting bytecode, ensuring portability and consistency across platforms.
