27.  difference b/t multiprocessing and multithreading
        Multithreading - Multiple threads within the same process(shared memory)
        multiprocessing - Multiple independent processes(separate memory)

        Multithreading
            one process ,multiple workers(threads)
            All share same memory space
        like: multiple chefs in one kitchen

        Multiprocessing:
            Multiple processes,each with its own memory
            communicate via IPC(pipes,queues)
        like: multiple kitchens working independently

        import threading
        import time

        def task():
            print("Task start")
            time.sleep(2)
            print("Task end")

        t1 = threading.Thread(target=task)
        t2 = threading.Thread(target=task)

        t1.start()
        t2.start()

        t1.join()
        t2.join()
------------------------------------------
        from multiprocessing import Process
        import time

        def task():
            print("Task start")
            time.sleep(2)
            print("Task end")

        p1 = Process(target=task)
        p2 = Process(target=task)

        p1.start()
        p2.start()

        p1.join()
        p2.join()

        | Feature           | Multithreading 🧵         | Multiprocessing ⚙️      |
        | ----------------- | ------------------------- | ----------------------- |
        | Memory            | Shared                    | Separate                |
        | Communication     | Easy (shared variables)   | Hard (IPC needed)       |
        | Speed (CPU tasks) | ❌ Limited (GIL in Python) | ✅ True parallelism      |
        | Speed (I/O tasks) | ✅ Very efficient          | ❌ Overkill              |
        | Overhead          | Low                       | High                    |
        | Fault Isolation   | ❌ One crash affects all   | ✅ Independent processes |


        🔴 The GIL Problem (Very Important)

        In Python:

            👉 Global Interpreter Lock (GIL)

                Only one thread executes Python bytecode at a time

        Impact:

            Multithreading ❌ NOT good for CPU-heavy tasks

            Multiprocessing ✅ best for CPU-heavy tasks

        🔹 Real-World Use Cases

           ✅ Use Multithreading When (I/O Bound)

                API calls

                File reading/writing

                Web scraping

                Database queries

        👉 Example:

                Web server handling multiple requests

        ✅ Use Multiprocessing When (CPU Bound)

            Image processing

            Machine learning

            Data transformation

            Heavy computations

        👉 Example:

            Training ML models

            Video encoding

            🔹 Real Production Example
            🚀 Web Backend

        Threads → handle multiple user requests (I/O)

        Processes → scale across CPU cores

        🧠 Data Pipeline

                Multiprocessing → parallel data processing

                Threads → async I/O operations

        🔹 Code Comparison (CPU Task)
        # CPU heavy task
        def compute():
            sum(i*i for i in range(10**7))

        👉 Threads → slow (GIL)
        👉 Processes → fast (parallel cores)

        🔹 Tech Lead Insights 💡
        ✅ Decision Rule

            I/O-bound → Multithreading

            CPU-bound → Multiprocessing

        ⚠️ Design Considerations

        Multiprocessing:

            Serialization cost (pickle)

            Memory duplication

        Multithreading:

        Race conditions

        Deadlocks

        🔴 Common Pitfalls
        ❌ Using threads for CPU-heavy work

        → No performance gain due to GIL

        ❌ Ignoring synchronization in threads

        → Data corruption

        ❌ Overusing multiprocessing

        → High memory usage + overhead

        🔹 Bonus: Hybrid Approach (Advanced)

        Modern systems use:

        Async + threads + processes

        Example:

        Async → network calls

        Threads → lightweight tasks

        Processes → heavy computation

        🔹 One-Line Interview Answer

        Multithreading uses shared memory and is ideal for I/O-bound tasks, while multiprocessing uses separate processes enabling true parallelism for CPU-bound tasks, avoiding Python’s GIL limitations.
