12.Use of super()
    call parent class method

    class A:
        def __init__(self):
            print("A")
    class B(A):
        def __init__(self):
            super().__init__()
            print("B")


13.If two parent classes have same method?
    class A:
    def show(self): print("A")

    class B:
        def show(self): print("B")

    class C(A, B):
        pass

    c = C()
    c.show()

    Python doesn't support overloading
    python avoids traditional overloading to keep syntax simple  uses dynamic typing instead
    Why python chose this design?
        Flexibility ->> Developers can still access data if needed
        Simplicity ->> No complex access rules like Java(private,public)
        Trust-Based design ->> python assumes you won't misuse internal data

