Why do we need fixtures in pytest?
    Fixtures in pytest are used to set up and provide reusable test data or resources to your tests.

    🔹 What is a Fixture?

            A fixture is a function that:

                Prepares data / environment before a test runs
                Optionally cleans up after the test
                Can be reused across multiple tests

            👉 Think: “test setup + dependency injection”

            import pytest

            @pytest.fixture
            def sample_data():
                return {"name": "Venkat", "age": 25}

            def test_user(sample_data):
                assert sample_data["name"] == "Venkat"
            👉 sample_data is automatically passed into the test

            🔹 Why Use Fixtures?

                    Without fixtures ❌:

                        def test_1():
                            data = {"name": "Venkat"}
                            ...

                        def test_2():
                            data = {"name": "Venkat"}
                            ...

                    With fixtures ✅:

                        @pytest.fixture
                        def data():
                            return {"name": "Venkat"}

                    👉 Avoid duplication

    🔹 Real-World Use Cases
            1. 🗄️ Database Setup

                @pytest.fixture
                def db_connection():
                    conn = connect_to_db()
                    yield conn
                    conn.close()

            👉 Automatically:

                    Opens DB before test
                    Closes DB after test

            2. 🌐 API Client (FastAPI / Django)

                @pytest.fixture
                def client():
                    from fastapi.testclient import TestClient
                    from app import app
                    return TestClient(app)

            👉 Used to test APIs easily

            3. 🔐 Authentication Setup
            @pytest.fixture
            def auth_user():
                return {"username": "admin", "token": "abc123"}
            🔹 yield in Fixtures (Important)
            @pytest.fixture
            def resource():
                print("Setup")
                yield "data"
                print("Teardown")

            👉 Execution flow:

                Setup runs
                Test runs
                Teardown runs
                🔹 Fixture Scope

        Control how often fixture runs:

            @pytest.fixture(scope="function")  # default
            @pytest.fixture(scope="module")
            @pytest.fixture(scope="session")
        Scope	                 Runs When
        function	             Every test
        module	                 Once per file
        session	                 Once for entire run
        🔹 Auto-use Fixtures
                @pytest.fixture(autouse=True)
                def setup():
                    print("Runs before every test")

                👉 No need to pass explicitly

        🔹 Parametrized Fixture
                @pytest.fixture(params=[1, 2, 3])
                def number(request):
                    return request.param

                def test_numbers(number):
                    assert number > 0

                👉 Runs test 3 times

        🔹 Key Benefits
                Reusability
                Cleaner tests
                Separation of setup logic
                Easy maintenance
                Built-in dependency injection
                🔹 Interview Answer (Strong)

        "Fixtures in pytest are used to manage test setup and teardown in a reusable way. They allow us to provide dependencies like database connections, API clients, or test data to multiple tests, improving code reusability and maintainability."
